[0.000, "o", "\u001b[?2004l\r\r\n"]
[0.006, "o", "\r\n\u001b[1m\u001b[0;36m══════════════════════════════════════════════════\u001b[0m\r\n\u001b[1m  Firewall RAG Manager — Demo\u001b[0m\r\n\u001b[1m\u001b[0;36m══════════════════════════════════════════════════\u001b[0m\r\n"]
[0.069, "o", "\u001b[0;32m✓ API healthy\u001b[0m\r\n"]
[0.000, "o", "\u001b[0;32m✓ Vector store: 306 documents across 4 devices (pa-fw01, fg-fw01, asa-fw01, ftd-fw01)\u001b[0m\r\n"]
[0.001, "o", "\r\n"]
[0.000, "o", "\u001b[1m\u001b[0;36m══════════════════════════════════════════════════\u001b[0m\r\n"]
[0.000, "o", "\u001b[1m  Part 1 — Semantic Search  (instant, no LLM)\u001b[0m\r\n"]
[0.000, "o", "\u001b[1m\u001b[0;36m══════════════════════════════════════════════════\u001b[0m\r\n"]
[0.000, "o", "\u001b[2m  Vector similarity search over 306 ingested policy documents\u001b[0m\r\n"]
[0.000, "o", "\r\n"]
[0.000, "o", "\u001b[1;33m▶ Shadow rule candidates — any/any policies that block rules below them\u001b[0m\r\n"]
[0.021, "o", "\u001b[2m  GET /api/v1/rag/search?q=shadow%20rule%20allow%20any%20any%20legacy%20temp&limit=4\u001b[0m\r\n\r\n"]
[0.133, "o", "  [pa-fw01 / paloalto]  allow-any-any-legacy  (security_rule)\r\n  Security Rule: allow-any-any-legacy Device: pa-fw01 (paloalto) Action: allow Enabled: True Source Zones: any Destination\r\n\r\n  [fg-fw01 / fortinet]  allow-all-temp  (security_rule)\r\n  Security Rule: allow-all-temp Device: fg-fw01 (fortinet) Action: allow Enabled: True Source Zones: any Destination Zones\r\n\r\n  [ftd-fw01 / cisco_ftd]  allow-all-legacy  (security_rule)\r\n  Security Rule: allow-all-legacy Device: ftd-fw01 (cisco_ftd) Action: allow Enabled: True Source Zones: any Destination Z\r\n\r\n  [pa-fw01 / paloalto]  block-servers-direct-internet  (security_rule)\r\n  Security Rule: block-servers-direct-internet Device: pa-fw01 (paloalto) Action: deny Enabled: True Source Zones: servers\r\n\r\n"]
[0.003, "o", "\r\n\u001b[1;33m▶ Redundant address objects — same IP defined under multiple names\u001b[0m\r\n"]
[0.031, "o", "\u001b[2m  GET /api/v1/rag/search?q=duplicate%20address%20object%20same%20IP%20redundant&limit=4\u001b[0m\r\n\r\n"]
[0.099, "o", "  [fg-fw01 / fortinet]  domain-controller  (address_object)\r\n  Address Object: domain-controller Type: network Value: 10.1.0.10/32 Description: Domain controller — DUPLICATE of ad-ser\r\n\r\n  [ftd-fw01 / cisco_ftd]  ad-server  (address_object)\r\n  Address Object: ad-server Type: host Value: 10.1.0.10 Description: AD server — DUPLICATE of domain-controller\r\n\r\n  [asa-fw01 / cisco_asa]  pub-web-ip  (address_object)\r\n  Address Object: pub-web-ip Type: host Value: 203.0.113.10\r\n"]
[0.000, "o", "\r\n  [asa-fw01 / cisco_asa]  pub-nat-ip  (address_object)\r\n  Address Object: pub-nat-ip Type: host Value: 203.0.113.1\r\n\r\n"]
[0.002, "o", "\r\n\u001b[1;33m▶ Inbound DNAT rules — public IPs mapped to internal servers\u001b[0m\r\n"]
[0.024, "o", "\u001b[2m  GET /api/v1/rag/search?q=DNAT%20inbound%20HTTPS%20web%20server%20port%20forward&limit=4\u001b[0m\r\n\r\n"]
[0.098, "o", "  [pa-fw01 / paloalto]  nat-inbound-http-web  (nat_rule)\r\n  NAT Rule: nat-inbound-http-web Device: pa-fw01 (paloalto) Type: dnat Enabled: True Source Zones: untrust Destination Zon\r\n\r\n  [pa-fw01 / paloalto]  nat-inbound-https-web  (nat_rule)\r\n  NAT Rule: nat-inbound-https-web Device: pa-fw01 (paloalto) Type: dnat Enabled: True Source Zones: untrust Destination Zo\r\n\r\n  [ftd-fw01 / cisco_ftd]  DNAT inbound HTTPS to DMZ web server  (nat_rule)\r\n  NAT Rule: DNAT inbound HTTPS to DMZ web server Device: ftd-fw01 (cisco_ftd) Type: dnat Enabled: True Source Zones: any D\r\n\r\n  [ftd-fw01 / cisco_ftd]  DNAT inbound HTTP to DMZ web server  (nat_rule)\r\n"]
[0.000, "o", "  NAT Rule: DNAT inbound HTTP to DMZ web server Device: ftd-fw01 (cisco_ftd) Type: dnat Enabled: True Source Zones: any De\r\n\r\n"]
[0.003, "o", "\r\n\u001b[1;33m▶ EDLs and threat feeds configured across devices\u001b[0m\r\n"]
[0.023, "o", "\u001b[2m  GET /api/v1/rag/search?q=external%20dynamic%20list%20threat%20feed%20blocklist&limit=4\u001b[0m\r\n\r\n"]
[0.098, "o", "  [ftd-fw01 / cisco_ftd]  custom-threat-url-list  (edl)\r\n  External Dynamic List / Threat Feed: custom-threat-url-list Type: url Device: ftd-fw01 (cisco_ftd) Description: Custom i\r\n\r\n  [fg-fw01 / fortinet]  threat-feed-bad-ips  (edl)\r\n  External Dynamic List / Threat Feed: threat-feed-bad-ips Type: ip Device: fg-fw01 (fortinet) Source: https://feeds.acmec\r\n\r\n  [fg-fw01 / fortinet]  threat-feed-malware-domains  (edl)\r\n  External Dynamic List / Threat Feed: threat-feed-malware-domains Type: domain Device: fg-fw01 (fortinet) Source: https:/\r\n\r\n"]
[0.000, "o", "  [pa-fw01 / paloalto]  edl-threat-intel-ips  (edl)\r\n  External Dynamic List / Threat Feed: edl-threat-intel-ips Type: ip Device: pa-fw01 (paloalto) Source: https://feeds.acme\r\n\r\n"]
[0.003, "o", "\r\n\u001b[1;33m▶ SSL inspection and decryption rules\u001b[0m\r\n"]
[0.022, "o", "\u001b[2m  GET /api/v1/rag/search?q=SSL%20TLS%20decryption%20inspection%20forward%20proxy&limit=3\u001b[0m\r\n\r\n"]
[0.097, "o", "  [fg-fw01 / fortinet]  ssl-inspect_allow-inbound-https-web  (decryption_rule)\r\n  Decryption Rule: ssl-inspect_allow-inbound-https-web Device: fg-fw01 (fortinet) Action: decrypt Type: ssl-forward-proxy \r\n\r\n  [fg-fw01 / fortinet]  ssl-inspect_allow-users-web  (decryption_rule)\r\n  Decryption Rule: ssl-inspect_allow-users-web Device: fg-fw01 (fortinet) Action: decrypt Type: ssl-forward-proxy Enabled:\r\n\r\n  [fg-fw01 / fortinet]  certificate-inspection  (decryption_profile)\r\n  Decryption Profile: certificate-inspection Device: fg-fw01 (fortinet) Minimum TLS: tls-1.1\r\n\r\n"]
[0.003, "o", "\r\n"]
[0.000, "o", "\u001b[1m\u001b[0;36m══════════════════════════════════════════════════\u001b[0m\r\n\u001b[1m  Part 2 — AI Chat  (RAG + Ollama LLM)\u001b[0m\r\n\u001b[1m\u001b[0;36m══════════════════════════════════════════════════\u001b[0m\r\n"]
[0.000, "o", "\u001b[2m  Each query retrieves relevant policy docs then asks the LLM to reason over them\u001b[0m\r\n\r\n  Run LLM queries? They take 15–60s each on CPU. [y/N] "]
[4.468, "o", "y"]
[1.428, "o", "\r\n"]
[0.008, "o", "\r\n\u001b[1;33m▶ Shadow rule analysis on pa-fw01\u001b[0m\r\n"]
[0.000, "o", "\u001b[2m  POST /api/v1/chat  (LLM response — may take 15–60s on CPU)\u001b[0m\r\n  \u001b[1mQ: Which rules on pa-fw01 are shadowed and can never be matched? Name them specifically.\u001b[0m\r\n\r\n"]
[0.275, "o", "y\r\n"]
[0.739, "o", "  Based on the provided context, there is only one rule on pa-fw01 that is \r\n  shadowed:\r\n  \r\n  1. allow-all-temp\r\n"]
[0.000, "o", "\r\n"]
[0.000, "o", "\u001b[1;33m▶ Redundant object analysis across all devices\u001b[0m\r\n"]
[0.000, "o", "\u001b[2m  POST /api/v1/chat  (LLM response — may take 15–60s on CPU)\u001b[0m\r\n"]
[0.000, "o", "  \u001b[1mQ: Find all address objects that have duplicate IP values across any of the four devices.\u001b[0m\r\n"]
[0.000, "o", "\r\n"]
[2.598, "o", "  After re-examining the retrieved context, I found another instance:\r\n  \r\n  1. Address Object: domain-controller (10.1.0.10/32) - Duplicate of ad-server\r\n  2. Address Object: internal-net (10.0.0.0/8) - Duplicate of corp-users\r\n  3. Address Object: ad-server (10.1.0.10/32) - Duplicate of domain-controller\r\n  \r\n  Note that the IP value 10.1.0.10 is a duplicate across two different address \r\n  objects, one on PAN-OS and one on another device.\r\n"]
[0.000, "o", "\r\n\u001b[1;33m▶ Cross-vendor translation — PAT rule\u001b[0m\r\n"]
[0.000, "o", "\u001b[2m  POST /api/v1/chat  (LLM response — may take 15–60s on CPU)\u001b[0m\r\n  \u001b[1mQ: Translate the outbound PAT NAT rule from pa-fw01 to equivalent FortiGate CLI syntax.\u001b[0m\r\n"]
[0.000, "o", "\r\n"]
[6.102, "o", "  To translate the outbound PAT NAT rule from pa-fw01 (Palo Alto Networks) to \r\n  equivalent FortiGate CLI syntax, I'll break down the original rule and recreate \r\n  it in FortiGate format.\r\n  \r\n  Original Rule:\r\n  ```\r\n  NAT Rule: nat-outbound-pat\r\n  Device: pa-fw01 (paloalto)\r\n  Type: pat\r\n  Enabled: True\r\n  Source Zones: trust, servers, vpn, dmz\r\n  Destination Zones: untrust\r\n  Original Source: any\r\n  Original Destination: any\r\n  Services: any\r\n  Translated Source: pub-nat-ip\r\n  Description: Outbound PAT — all internal zones to single public IP\r\n"]
[0.000, "o", "  ```\r\n  \r\n  FortiGate Equivalent:\r\n  ```fortinet\r\n  config firewall nat\r\n    edit 1\r\n      source-addr \"pub-nat-ip\"\r\n"]
[0.000, "o", "      dest-addr \"any\"\r\n"]
[0.000, "o", "      mode pat\r\n      set service any\r\n      set log disable\r\n      next-end\r\n  end\r\n"]
[0.000, "o", "  ```\r\n  \r\n"]
[0.000, "o", "  Note that the FortiGate NAT rule syntax is slightly different from Palo Alto \r\n  Networks. The main differences are:\r\n  \r\n"]
[0.000, "o", "  * `source-addr` and `dest-addr` instead of `Original Source` and `Original \r\n  Destination`\r\n"]
[0.000, "o", "  * `mode pat` to set the mode to PAT (Port Address Translation)\r\n  * `set service any` to allow all services\r\n"]
[0.000, "o", "  * `set log disable` to disable logging for this rule\r\n  \r\n  Please verify that this translation meets your requirements.\r\n"]
[0.000, "o", "\r\n"]
[0.000, "o", "\u001b[1;33m▶ Policy comparison — inbound access\u001b[0m\r\n"]
[0.000, "o", "\u001b[2m  POST /api/v1/chat  (LLM response — may take 15–60s on CPU)\u001b[0m\r\n"]
[0.000, "o", "  \u001b[1mQ: Compare the inbound security rules between pa-fw01 and fg-fw01. What does one allow that the other doesn't?\u001b[0m\r\n\r\n"]
[6.482, "o", "  Based on the provided context, here's a comparison of the inbound security \r\n  rules between pa-fw01 (Palo Alto Networks) and fg-fw01 (Fortinet):\r\n  \r\n  **pa-fw01:**\r\n  \r\n  * allow-inbound-http-web:\r\n  \t+ Allows HTTP traffic from untrust to dmz\r\n  \t+ Redirects to HTTPS via app\r\n  \t+ Services: application-default\r\n  \t+ Applications: web-browsing\r\n  * allow-inbound-https-web:\r\n  \t+ Allows HTTPS traffic from untrust to dmz\r\n  \t+ Full inspection\r\n  \t+ Services: application-default\r\n  \t+ Applications: ssl\r\n  \r\n  **fg-fw01:**\r\n  \r\n  * allow-inbound-http-web:\r\n  \t+ Allows HTTP traffic from untrust to dmz\r\n  \t+ Redirects to HTTPS via app\r\n  \t+ Services: HTTP\r\n  * allow-inbound-https-web:\r\n  \t+ Allows HTTPS traffic from untrust to dmz\r\n  \t+ Full inspection\r\n  \t+ Services: HTTPS\r\n  \r\n  Key differences:\r\n  \r\n  1. **Application Control**: pa-fw01's allow-inbound-http-web and \r\n  allow-inbound-https-web rules apply application control, specifically \r\n  web-browsing for HTTP and ssl for HTTPS, whereas fg-fw01 does not ha"]
[0.000, "o", "ve explicit \r\n  application control.\r\n  2. **Services Mapping**: While both devices use the same services (HTTP and \r\n  HTTPS), pa-fw01 maps them to specific applications (web-browsing and ssl), \r\n  whereas fg-fw01 uses the service names directly.\r\n  \r\n  In summary, pa-fw01 allows application control for HTTP and HTTPS traffic, \r\n  which is not present in fg-fw01.\r\n"]
[0.001, "o", "\r\n\r\n"]
[0.000, "o", "\u001b[1m\u001b[0;36m══════════════════════════════════════════════════\u001b[0m\r\n"]
[0.000, "o", "\u001b[1m  Done\u001b[0m\r\n"]
